The article highlights the partnership between the United States and China in combatting climate change. The two countries have been working together since 2013 and have made significant progress in galvanizing global action to build a green, low-carbon, and climate-resilient world. They have both deposited their instruments to join the Paris Agreement and are urging other countries to do the same. The United States and China will formulate and publish their respective strategies for low-greenhouse gas emission development and will hold technical exchanges on this topic. They are also committed to working with other countries to advance the post-Paris negotiation process. Additionally, the two countries will work together to reach an agreement on reducing the use of hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs) and will collaborate on research regarding the safe use of alternatives. They also support the adoption of a global market-based measure to address carbon emissions from international aviation. The article mentions the achievements of the U.S.-China Climate Change Working Group and U.S.-China Clean Energy Research Center and the commitment to further enhance bilateral cooperation on climate change. Both countries are taking ambitious domestic actions to promote the transition towards green, low-carbon, and climate-resilient economies. Finally, the United States and China are committed to providing financial assistance to developing countries to address climate change.